Everyday English for You

M.6 Review: From Gaming to Speaking

Current Level: ฟังได้แต่ไม่รู้เรื่องถ้าไม่เปิด sub eng, พอแปลได้คร่าวๆ, คิดประโยคไว้ในหัวแต่พูดไม่ได้เพราะกลัวพลาด, อ่านได้, เล่นเกมภาษาอังกฤษได้

1. Building Your Confidence

The Most Important Rule: It's Okay to Make Mistakes!

Your goal is communication, not perfection. Many Thais feel 'เกรงใจ' (kreng jai), but people appreciate the effort you make to speak their language. Let's start!

Pronunciation Foundation

Let's listen to a general guide and then focus on some key sounds that are different from Thai.

  • Final Consonants: Say the whole word! In English, the sound at the end is important.
    "dog-uh", "cat-t", "book-k"
  • 'R' vs 'L' Sounds: Practice the tongue position.
    'R' (red): curl tongue back. 'L' (light): tongue tip touches behind teeth.
  • 'Th' Sounds (/θ/, /ð/): New sounds! Put your tongue between your teeth.
    'th'in (like 'f' but with tongue), 'th'is (vibrate your voice).
  • Word Stress: English has a rhythm. Some parts are louder.
    pho-TO-gra-pher, not pho-to-gra-pher.

2. Simple Grammar Rules

Sentence Structure: S-V-O

English sentences almost always follow this order: Subject (who/what) + Verb (action) + Object (receives action). It's more strict than Thai.

I play games.

The Present Simple Tense

Use it for habits, routines, and facts. Things you do every day!

(+) Positive

I/You/We/They play.

He/She/It plays. (Don't forget the 's'!)

(-) Negative

I/You/We/They don't play.

He/She/It doesn't play.

(?) Question

Do you/we/they play?

Does he/she/it play?

Note: We use 'do/does' to ask questions, not 'ไหม' (mái) at the end.

4. Practice Makes Progress!

Exercise 1: Fill in the Blanks

1. She coffee every morning.

2. We games on the weekend.

3. He (not) like spicy food.

4. you study English?

Exercise 2: Translate and Speak!

Translate these Thai sentences to English, then say them out loud.

  • "ฉันกินข้าว" (chan gin kâao)
    I eat rice.
  • "เขาทำงานที่กรุงเทพ" (kăo tam-ngaan tîi grung-têp)
    He works in Bangkok.
  • "พวกเขาไม่ดื่มชา" (pûak-kăo mâi dèum chaa)
    They don't drink tea.

5. Let's Talk!

A. Introduce Yourself

Tip: Using your nickname is very common and friendly!

"Hi! My name is [Your Name]. I'm from Thailand. I like to [hobby 1] and [hobby 2]."

B. Talk About Your Day

Try to describe 3-4 simple actions from your day.

"Well, I wake up at [time]. Then, I [action]. After that, I [action]. In the evening, I usually [action]."

C. Ask Simple Questions

Keep the conversation going!

  • What do you do in the morning?
  • Do you like coffee or tea?
  • What do you do on the weekends?
